.\nGate 15: PASS — The Chorus is a clear, memorable summary of the verse's action.\nGate 16: PASS — Verses maintain a stable AABB, 8-syllable iambic tetrameter.\nGate 17: PASS — Deep meaning (e.g., \"the wall comes down\") is compressed into simple lyrics.\nGate 18: PASS — Verses are the bait (narrative setup), Chorus is the barb (the core truth).\nGate 19: PASS — Bridge contains vocative \"O Lord\" (Law 84) and first-person \"we\" (Law 85).\nGate 20: PASS — Bridge contains the hinge: \"Your Spirit gives the power / So we can speak Your Name.\"\nGate 21: PASS — AABB rhyme scheme is used throughout with exact rhymes. (V1: feet/street, came/flame; C: way/day, see/be; V2: old/told, down/town; B: power/hour, Name/same).\nGate 22: PASS — The final output is in a single fenced code block with the <code>text</code> tag.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines are 7-8 syllables, confirmed by count.\nGate 24: PASS — Title \"The Way They Spoke\" is 4 words, concrete, from the Chorus, and memorable.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Title: The Way They Spoke\nStyle: Folk rock, male vocalist, gospel choir backing vocals, Hammond B3 organ, upright piano, simple driving drum beat, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nThey shook the dust from off their feet (A)\nAnd walked another city street (A)\nA new town where the Word became (B)\nA holy fire, a holy flame (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nIt was the way they chose to speak (A)\nThat made the strong and made the weak (A)\nA crowd of Jew and Greek to see (B)\nThe one new man they came to be (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nThey read the scrolls of what was old (A)\nThe story that the prophets told (A)\nAnd in that place the wall came down (B)\nRight in the center of the town (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nIt was the way they chose to speak (A)\nThat made the strong and made the weak (A)\nA crowd of Jew and Greek to see (B)\nThe one new man they came to be (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nYour Spirit gives the power (A)\nFor this appointed hour (A)\nSo we can speak Your Name (B)\nAnd see You do the same (B)\n\n[Outro]\nO Lord, You do the same\nLet us now speak Your Name\nLet us now speak Your Name\nThe same.\n\n[End]\n</code></pre>",
      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The strategic, unified, and powerful manner of Paul and Barnabas’s gospel proclamation in the synagogue at Iconium.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** This method of proclamation was supernaturally effective, resulting in the salvation of a large, mixed multitude of both Jews and Greeks, thereby creating a new community in Christ that transcended ethnic lines.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** Spirit-empowered proclamation of the gospel, strategically delivered, has the divine power to create a large and unified body of believers from previously divided peoples.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The strategic, unified, and powerful manner of Paul and Barnabas’s gospel proclamation in the synagogue at Iconium.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> This method of proclamation was supernaturally effective, resulting in the salvation of a large, mixed multitude of both Jews and Greeks, thereby creating a new community in Christ that transcended ethnic lines.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> Spirit-empowered proclamation of the gospel, strategically delivered, has the divine power to create a large and unified body of believers from previously divided peoples.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The thesis of Acts is the Spirit-empowered witness to the resurrected Christ spreading from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). This verse is a concise snapshot of that mission in action during the first missionary journey. It perfectly illustrates the strategic pattern (\"to the Jew first,\" Rom 1:16) and the supernatural result (Gentile inclusion) that defines the book's second half.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse opens the pericope (\"the literary unit\") of the ministry in Iconium (Acts 14:1-7). It immediately follows the missionaries' expulsion from Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:50-52), where they \"shook the dust from their feet.\" This verse shows their resilience and unwavering commitment to the same mission strategy in the next city on their route. The success described here sets up the conflict that follows in verse 2.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** The genre is historical narrative. The primary hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual report of events. While descriptive, the recurring pattern of synagogue ministry in Acts presents it as an exemplary apostolic strategy, demonstrating a theological principle: the gospel goes \"to the Jew first, and also to the Greek\" (Rom 1:16).\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** This event occurs during the Church Age (the dispensation of Grace), around AD 47-48. The New Covenant is the operative redemptive economy. The wall of hostility between Jew and Gentile is being demolished in practice (Eph 2:14) as the Church, the \"one new man,\" is being formed city by city.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The preceding context is persecution and expulsion from Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:50). The subsequent context is the division and persecution that arises in Iconium precisely because of the success described in this verse (Acts 14:2-5). This verse is the hinge of success that provokes the inevitable opposition.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This verse exemplifies a key pattern in Acts.\n    *   **Synagogue-First Strategy:** Acts 13:14 [Pericope: Acts 13:13–43 · source: NA28]; Acts 17:1-2 [Pericope: Acts 17:1–9 · source: NA28]; Acts 18:4 [Pericope: Acts 18:1–17 · source: NA28].\n    *   **Mixed Congregation Forms:** Acts 13:48 [Pericope: Acts 13:44–52 · source: NA28]; Acts 17:4 [Pericope: Acts 17:1–9 · source: NA28]; Acts 17:12 [Pericope: Acts 17:10–15 · source: NA28].\n    *   **The Gospel's Power to Save:** Romans 1:16 [Pericope: Rom 1:16–17 · source: NA28]; 1 Corinthians 1:18 [Pericope: 1 Cor 1:18–25 · source: NA28].\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The thesis of Acts is the Spirit-empowered witness to the resurrected Christ spreading from Jerusalem to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8). This verse is a concise snapshot of that mission in action during the first missionary journey. It perfectly illustrates the strategic pattern (\"to the Jew first,\" Rom 1:16) and the supernatural result (Gentile inclusion) that defines the book's second half.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This verse opens the pericope (\"the literary unit\") of the ministry in Iconium (Acts 14:1-7). It immediately follows the missionaries' expulsion from Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:50-52), where they \"shook the dust from their feet.\" This verse shows their resilience and unwavering commitment to the same mission strategy in the next city on their route. The success described here sets up the conflict that follows in verse 2.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic:</strong> The genre is historical narrative. The primary hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a factual report of events. While descriptive, the recurring pattern of synagogue ministry in Acts presents it as an exemplary apostolic strategy, demonstrating a theological principle: the gospel goes \"to the Jew first, and also to the Greek\" (Rom 1:16).</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> This event occurs during the Church Age (the dispensation of Grace), around AD 47-48. The New Covenant is the operative redemptive economy. The wall of hostility between Jew and Gentile is being demolished in practice (Eph 2:14) as the Church, the \"one new man,\" is being formed city by city.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors:</strong> The preceding context is persecution and expulsion from Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:50). The subsequent context is the division and persecution that arises in Iconium precisely because of the success described in this verse (Acts 14:2-5). This verse is the hinge of success that provokes the inevitable opposition.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This verse exemplifies a key pattern in Acts.<ul>\n<li><strong>Synagogue-First Strategy:</strong> Acts 13:14 [Pericope: Acts 13:13–43 · source: NA28]; Acts 17:1-2 [Pericope: Acts 17:1–9 · source: NA28]; Acts 18:4 [Pericope: Acts 18:1–17 · source: NA28].</li>\n<li><strong>Mixed Congregation Forms:</strong> Acts 13:48 [Pericope: Acts 13:44–52 · source: NA28]; Acts 17:4 [Pericope: Acts 17:1–9 · source: NA28]; Acts 17:12 [Pericope: Acts 17:10–15 · source: NA28].</li>\n<li><strong>The Gospel's Power to Save:</strong> Romans 1:16 [Pericope: Rom 1:16–17 · source: NA28]; 1 Corinthians 1:18 [Pericope: 1 Cor 1:18–25 · source: NA28].</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event takes place during Paul’s First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to c. AD 47-48. This is during the reign of Roman Emperor Claudius (AD 41-54).\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1030m) was a strategic city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on a major trade route. It was a Hellenized city with a significant Jewish population, making its synagogue a key starting point for mission.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The original audience of Acts was Theophilus (Acts 1:1), likely a high-ranking Roman official, and the broader nascent Christian community. The account would have served to document the historical and theological legitimacy of the Christian movement, demonstrating its roots in Judaism and its Spirit-ordained expansion to the Gentiles.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke, the \"beloved physician\" (Col 4:14) and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing as a careful historian (Luke 1:1-4). His purpose is to provide an \"orderly account\" of the Church's origins and expansion under the direct guidance of the Holy Spirit.\n*   **Socio-Political Background:** Iconium was a prosperous city in a region known for its mix of native Phrygian culture, Greek influence (Hellenism), and Roman administration. The Jewish synagogue served as a religious and social center for the Jewish diaspora and also attracted \"God-fearers\"—Gentiles who were drawn to Jewish monotheism and ethics but had not fully converted (Tier 1 source: Josephus and inscriptions attest to this widespread phenomenon). This pre-existing interface between Jewish and Gentile worlds was the fertile soil God used for the gospel's initial spread.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> The event takes place during Paul’s First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to c. AD 47-48. This is during the reign of Roman Emperor Claudius (AD 41-54).</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong> Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1030m) was a strategic city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on a major trade route. It was a Hellenized city with a significant Jewish population, making its synagogue a key starting point for mission.</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> The original audience of Acts was Theophilus (Acts 1:1), likely a high-ranking Roman official, and the broader nascent Christian community. The account would have served to document the historical and theological legitimacy of the Christian movement, demonstrating its roots in Judaism and its Spirit-ordained expansion to the Gentiles.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke, the \"beloved physician\" (Col 4:14) and traveling companion of Paul, is the author, writing as a careful historian (Luke 1:1-4). His purpose is to provide an \"orderly account\" of the Church's origins and expansion under the direct guidance of the Holy Spirit.</li>\n<li><strong>Socio-Political Background:</strong> Iconium was a prosperous city in a region known for its mix of native Phrygian culture, Greek influence (Hellenism), and Roman administration. The Jewish synagogue served as a religious and social center for the Jewish diaspora and also attracted \"God-fearers\"—Gentiles who were drawn to Jewish monotheism and ethics but had not fully converted (Tier 1 source: Josephus and inscriptions attest to this widespread phenomenon). This pre-existing interface between Jewish and Gentile worlds was the fertile soil God used for the gospel's initial spread.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n*   **Literal-Primary Filter:** The verse reports a historical event: Paul and Barnabas entered the synagogue in Iconium, preached effectively, and many Jews and Greeks believed.\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The key to the verse is the adverbial phrase λαλῆσαι οὕτως (*lalēsai houtōs*, \"to speak in such a way\"). The adverb οὕτως (*houtōs*, \"thus, so, in this manner\") is qualitative. Luke isn't just saying they spoke; he's highlighting the *character* of their speech. This points back to the boldness (παρρησία, *parrēsia*) and Spirit-empowerment that characterizes apostolic preaching throughout Acts (cf. Acts 4:31). The ὥστε (*hōste*) + infinitive clause indicates the result: their manner of speaking directly produced belief.\n*   **Wordplay:** There is no overt wordplay, but the construction Ἰουδαίων τε καὶ Ἑλλήνων (*Ioudaiōn te kai Hellēnōn*, \"both of Jews and of Greeks\") uses a τε καί (*te kai*) correlative conjunction. This is a closer link than a simple καί (*kai*, \"and\"), emphasizing the formation of a single, unified group from two distinct peoples. It’s a grammatical picture of the \"middle wall of partition\" being broken down (Eph 2:14).\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The central \"image\" is the synagogue. The synagogue was the beachhead for the gospel in the diaspora. **Why this image?** It establishes the gospel's continuity with God's promises to Israel. The apostles did not preach a new religion from scratch; they entered the existing assembly of God's people and announced the fulfillment of their Scriptures in Jesus the Messiah (Acts 13:26-33). The synagogue was the place where the Old Testament was read, providing the immediate textual foundation for their Christ-centered message.\n*   **Common Misreadings Flag:**\n    *   *Misreading:* Paul’s success was due to his personal rhetorical skill and eloquence.\n    *   *Why wrong:* While Paul was highly educated, Acts consistently attributes the power of apostolic preaching not to human technique but to the Holy Spirit (Acts 1:8; 4:31; 1 Cor 2:1-5). The οὕτως (*houtōs*, \"in such a way\") points to the divine quality and power of the proclamation, not merely human oratory.\n    *   *Cross-references:* 1 Corinthians 2:4; 1 Thessalonians 1:5.\n    *   *Correct reading:* The apostles spoke in a manner empowered by the Holy Spirit, which is why their message had such a profound, converting effect.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Literal-Primary Filter:</strong> The verse reports a historical event: Paul and Barnabas entered the synagogue in Iconium, preached effectively, and many Jews and Greeks believed.</li>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong> The key to the verse is the adverbial phrase λαλῆσαι οὕτως (<em>lalēsai houtōs</em>, \"to speak in such a way\"). The adverb οὕτως (<em>houtōs</em>, \"thus, so, in this manner\") is qualitative. Luke isn't just saying they spoke; he's highlighting the <em>character</em> of their speech. This points back to the boldness (παρρησία, <em>parrēsia</em>) and Spirit-empowerment that characterizes apostolic preaching throughout Acts (cf. Acts 4:31). The ὥστε (<em>hōste</em>) + infinitive clause indicates the result: their manner of speaking directly produced belief.</li>\n<li><strong>Wordplay:</strong> There is no overt wordplay, but the construction Ἰουδαίων τε καὶ Ἑλλήνων (<em>Ioudaiōn te kai Hellēnōn</em>, \"both of Jews and of Greeks\") uses a τε καί (<em>te kai</em>) correlative conjunction. This is a closer link than a simple καί (<em>kai</em>, \"and\"), emphasizing the formation of a single, unified group from two distinct peoples. It’s a grammatical picture of the \"middle wall of partition\" being broken down (Eph 2:14).</li>\n<li><strong>Imagery &amp; Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):</strong> The central \"image\" is the synagogue. The synagogue was the beachhead for the gospel in the diaspora. <strong>Why this image?</strong> It establishes the gospel's continuity with God's promises to Israel. The apostles did not preach a new religion from scratch; they entered the existing assembly of God's people and announced the fulfillment of their Scriptures in Jesus the Messiah (Acts 13:26-33). The synagogue was the place where the Old Testament was read, providing the immediate textual foundation for their Christ-centered message.</li>\n<li><strong>Common Misreadings Flag:</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Misreading:</em> Paul’s success was due to his personal rhetorical skill and eloquence.</li>\n<li><em>Why wrong:</em> While Paul was highly educated, Acts consistently attributes the power of apostolic preaching not to human technique but to the Holy Spirit (Acts 1:8; 4:31; 1 Cor 2:1-5). The οὕτως (<em>houtōs</em>, \"in such a way\") points to the divine quality and power of the proclamation, not merely human oratory.</li>\n<li><em>Cross-references:</em> 1 Corinthians 2:4; 1 Thessalonians 1:5.</li>\n<li><em>Correct reading:</em> The apostles spoke in a manner empowered by the Holy Spirit, which is why their message had such a profound, converting effect.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment:**\n    *   **[PROPHECY]** This event is a direct fulfillment of Isaiah's prophecies that God's salvation would reach the Gentiles and be a light to the nations (Isa 49:6), a verse Paul explicitly quoted in the previous city (Acts 13:47).\n    *   **[TYPE]** The gathering of a mixed assembly of Jews and Gentiles into one believing body is a living type, or prefigurement, of the \"one new man\" described doctrinally in Ephesians 2:15, and the final ingathering of \"a great multitude that no one could number, from every nation, from all tribes and peoples and languages\" (Rev 7:9).\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** This verse is a hinge in the trajectory of the \"People of God\" motif.\n    *   Genesis 12:3: The promise to Abraham that in him \"all the families of the earth shall be blessed.\"\n    *   Isaiah 49:6: The Servant of the LORD will be a \"light for the nations.\"\n    *   Joel 2:28-29: God will pour out His Spirit on \"all flesh.\"\n    *   Matthew 28:19: The Great Commission to make disciples of \"all nations.\"\n    *   Acts 2:39: The promise is for the Jews, their children, and \"for all who are far off.\"\n    *   **Acts 14:1 (this passage):** The practical, on-the-ground fulfillment of this trajectory, as the Church is built from both Jew and Gentile.\n    *   The *hinge-of-hinges* is the Cross and Resurrection, which made this new, unified body possible.\n    *   The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the presentation of the unified Bride to Christ (Eph 5:27) and the diverse, redeemed multitude worshipping the Lamb (Rev 7:9).\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   ☐ Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): Demonstrates that salvation comes through believing the proclaimed gospel message.\n    *   ☐ Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"): The effectiveness of the preaching is implicitly attributed to the Spirit's power.\n    *   ☐ Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"): Shows the local church being born, composed of both Jews and Gentiles.\n    *   ☐ Missiology (sub-locus of Ecclesiology): Provides a paradigm for missionary strategy—contextualized proclamation beginning with those who have prior revelation.\n*   **Tripartite Synthesis:** Conservative Christian commentators emphasize this as a model of Spirit-empowered, strategic missions. Jewish scholars of the period note the synagogue's role as a hub for diaspora life and its openness to Gentile \"God-fearers,\" providing the historical context for Luke's account. Midrashic traditions do not directly comment on NT events, but their emphasis on the future ingathering of righteous Gentiles at the end of days provides a theological backdrop against which the apostles' work can be seen as an inaugurated fulfillment. All streams converge on the synagogue as the natural starting point for a message claiming to be the fulfillment of Hebrew Scripture.\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:** This passage points to Christ as the substance of the apostolic message. Though His name is not in this verse, the content of what they \"spoke\" is consistently the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus as the fulfillment of the Old Testament (cf. Acts 13:23-39). Christ is the one in whom the believing Jew and Greek find their unity.\n",
