i>☐ Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): Demonstrates that salvation comes through believing the proclaimed gospel message.</li>\n<li>☐ Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"): The effectiveness of the preaching is implicitly attributed to the Spirit's power.</li>\n<li>☐ Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"): Shows the local church being born, composed of both Jews and Gentiles.</li>\n<li>☐ Missiology (sub-locus of Ecclesiology): Provides a paradigm for missionary strategy—contextualized proclamation beginning with those who have prior revelation.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Tripartite Synthesis:</strong> Conservative Christian commentators emphasize this as a model of Spirit-empowered, strategic missions. Jewish scholars of the period note the synagogue's role as a hub for diaspora life and its openness to Gentile \"God-fearers,\" providing the historical context for Luke's account. Midrashic traditions do not directly comment on NT events, but their emphasis on the future ingathering of righteous Gentiles at the end of days provides a theological backdrop against which the apostles' work can be seen as an inaugurated fulfillment. All streams converge on the synagogue as the natural starting point for a message claiming to be the fulfillment of Hebrew Scripture.</li>\n<li><strong>Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:</strong> This passage points to Christ as the substance of the apostolic message. Though His name is not in this verse, the content of what they \"spoke\" is consistently the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus as the fulfillment of the Old Testament (cf. Acts 13:23-39). Christ is the one in whom the believing Jew and Greek find their unity.</li>\n</ul>",
