or You bear witness.\"\nGate 21: PASS — AABB rhyme scheme is declared and strictly followed with exact rhymes.\nGate 22: PASS — Final output is a single fenced code block with the <code>text</code> tag.\nGate 23: PASS — All lines counted and confirmed to be 7-8 syllables.\nGate 24: PASS — Title is 4 words, from the core message, memorable and non-abstract.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Title: The Word of His Grace\nStyle: Raw folk, Male vocalist, Resonator guitar, Stomp box, Upright bass, Large room acoustics, live room bleed, thick mid-range, wooden resonance, environmental air, no noise reduction, raw analog capture, tape saturation\nDirectives: No song introduction. Abrupt start.\n\n[Verse 1]\nA long time they remained (A)\nHis truth they explained (A)\nThough minds were enraged (B)\nThey turned a new page (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nHe bears witness to the Word (A)\nThe best news ever heard (A)\nThe Word of all His grace (B)\nConfirmed in time and space (B)\n\n[Verse 2]\nSo speak it clear and bold (A)\nA story to be told (A)\nRely on Him alone (B)\nTo make His power known (B)\n\n[Bridge]\nThrough these hands, O Lord, now move (A)\nYour faithfulness please prove (A)\nI will speak, for You bear witness (B)\nMy strength in all my weakness (B)\n\n[Chorus]\nHe bears witness to the Word (A)\nThe best news ever heard (A)\nThe Word of all His grace (B)\nConfirmed in time and space (B)\n\n[Outro]\nBy signs their hands had shown (A)\nHis grace was truly known (A)\nHis grace is known (B)\nHis grace is known (B)\n\n[End]\n</code></pre>",
      "phase_b_thesis": "### The Thesis\n\n*   **Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):** The apostolic ministry of Paul and Barnabas in Iconium.\n*   **Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):** It was a sustained period of bold, Lord-dependent preaching, which the Lord Himself authenticated with signs and wonders as a direct testimony to the message of His grace.\n*   **Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):** The Lord confirms the bold preaching of His gospel of grace with His own divine witness.\n",
      "phase_b_thesis_html": "<h3>The Thesis</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Subject (\"What is the author talking about?\"):</strong> The apostolic ministry of Paul and Barnabas in Iconium.</li>\n<li><strong>Complement (\"What is the author saying about that subject?\"):</strong> It was a sustained period of bold, Lord-dependent preaching, which the Lord Himself authenticated with signs and wonders as a direct testimony to the message of His grace.</li>\n<li><strong>Big Idea (\"the one truth this passage is teaching\"):</strong> The Lord confirms the bold preaching of His gospel of grace with His own divine witness.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_c_big_picture": "### Big Picture: Where this passage fits\n\n*   **Whole-Book Thesis & Passage's Role:** The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to Rome, fulfilling Christ's commission in Acts 1:8. This verse provides a perfect microcosm of that mission: human proclamation empowered and authenticated by divine action. It demonstrates the *how* of the book's *what*.\n*   **Discourse / Section Arc:** This verse is a summary statement within the Iconium episode (Acts 14:1-7) of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It serves as the hinge between the initial opposition (14:2) and the climactic plot that forces the apostles to flee (14:5-6), explaining why they persisted in the face of hostility.\n*   **Genre & Hermeneutic:** The genre is **Historical Narrative**. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a faithful description of what happened, not necessarily a direct prescription for all ministry in all times. The pattern—bold preaching of grace, reliance on the Lord, and divine confirmation—is a timeless principle, while the specific manifestation of \"signs and wonders\" is described as a feature of the foundational, apostolic era (Heb 2:3-4).\n*   **Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):** The passage is firmly located in the **Church Age** (Dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is in effect, and the gospel is moving out to the Gentiles in fulfillment of the Great Commission, demonstrating that the wall of partition has been broken down (Eph 2:14).\n*   **Author & Attribution:** The author is Luke the physician, companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing his second volume to Theophilus (Luke 1:1-4; Acts 1:1). The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely from Rome, before the Neronian persecution and Paul's death.\n*   **Gravitational Neighbors:** The verse is a response to the \"unbelieving Jews\" who \"stirred up the Gentiles and poisoned their minds against the brothers\" (Acts 14:2). It explains their persistence. It is followed by the escalation of this division into a city-wide schism and a violent plot (Acts 14:4-5), which finally forces their departure.\n*   **Sister-Passage Parallels:** This verse joins a canonical chorus describing the synergy of human proclamation and divine confirmation. The Lord \"working with them and confirming the word by the signs that followed\" (Mark 16:20) is the paradigm. Hebrews 2:4 states that God bore witness to the apostolic message \"by signs and wonders and various miracles and by gifts of the Holy Spirit.\" The content of the message is consistently \"the word of his grace\" (Acts 20:24, 32), and the required human posture is boldness (παρρησία, *parrēsia*) rooted in the Spirit's power (Acts 4:31).\n",
      "phase_c_big_picture_html": "<h3>Big Picture: Where this passage fits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Whole-Book Thesis &amp; Passage's Role:</strong> The book of Acts chronicles the Spirit-empowered expansion of the church from Jerusalem to Rome, fulfilling Christ's commission in Acts 1:8. This verse provides a perfect microcosm of that mission: human proclamation empowered and authenticated by divine action. It demonstrates the <em>how</em> of the book's <em>what</em>.</li>\n<li><strong>Discourse / Section Arc:</strong> This verse is a summary statement within the Iconium episode (Acts 14:1-7) of Paul's First Missionary Journey (Acts 13:1–14:28). It serves as the hinge between the initial opposition (14:2) and the climactic plot that forces the apostles to flee (14:5-6), explaining why they persisted in the face of hostility.</li>\n<li><strong>Genre &amp; Hermeneutic:</strong> The genre is <strong>Historical Narrative</strong>. The governing hermeneutic (\"a rule for interpreting Scripture — the principle by which a text is read\") is to read this as a faithful description of what happened, not necessarily a direct prescription for all ministry in all times. The pattern—bold preaching of grace, reliance on the Lord, and divine confirmation—is a timeless principle, while the specific manifestation of \"signs and wonders\" is described as a feature of the foundational, apostolic era (Heb 2:3-4).</li>\n<li><strong>Salvation-Historical Locator (Covenantal + Dispensational):</strong> The passage is firmly located in the <strong>Church Age</strong> (Dispensation of Grace). The New Covenant is in effect, and the gospel is moving out to the Gentiles in fulfillment of the Great Commission, demonstrating that the wall of partition has been broken down (Eph 2:14).</li>\n<li><strong>Author &amp; Attribution:</strong> The author is Luke the physician, companion of Paul (Col 4:14; 2 Tim 4:11), writing his second volume to Theophilus (Luke 1:1-4; Acts 1:1). The work is dated conservatively to the early AD 60s, likely from Rome, before the Neronian persecution and Paul's death.</li>\n<li><strong>Gravitational Neighbors:</strong> The verse is a response to the \"unbelieving Jews\" who \"stirred up the Gentiles and poisoned their minds against the brothers\" (Acts 14:2). It explains their persistence. It is followed by the escalation of this division into a city-wide schism and a violent plot (Acts 14:4-5), which finally forces their departure.</li>\n<li><strong>Sister-Passage Parallels:</strong> This verse joins a canonical chorus describing the synergy of human proclamation and divine confirmation. The Lord \"working with them and confirming the word by the signs that followed\" (Mark 16:20) is the paradigm. Hebrews 2:4 states that God bore witness to the apostolic message \"by signs and wonders and various miracles and by gifts of the Holy Spirit.\" The content of the message is consistently \"the word of his grace\" (Acts 20:24, 32), and the required human posture is boldness (παρρησία, <em>parrēsia</em>) rooted in the Spirit's power (Acts 4:31).</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_d_setting": "### Setting: The original audience's world\n\n*   **Historical Context & Chronology:** The event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48. This is the very beginning of the organized Gentile mission.\n*   **Geospatial Data & Physical Geography:** Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1027m) was a strategic city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on the major east-west trade route. Its prominence made it a natural hub for missionary activity.\n*   **Original Audience Identification:** The immediate audience of the book was a man named Theophilus (Acts 1:1), likely a high-ranking Roman official and a new believer. The wider audience was the burgeoning church, which needed a divinely inspired account of its own origins and the authentication of the apostolic gospel.\n*   **Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):** Luke writes as a meticulous historian (Luke 1:3) and a theologian. His purpose is to show Theophilus the certainty of the things he has been taught by demonstrating the unstoppable, Spirit-directed advance of the gospel from its Jewish center in Jerusalem to the heart of the Gentile world in Rome.\n*   **Socio-Political Background:** Iconium was a Hellenized city with a significant Jewish population and a synagogue, which served as Paul's customary entry point for ministry. As part of the Roman Empire, it was under the rule of Roman law, which at this early stage was often indifferent or situationally hostile to the new Christian faith, depending on local politics and the influence of opponents.\n",
      "phase_d_setting_html": "<h3>Setting: The original audience's world</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Historical Context &amp; Chronology:</strong> The event occurs during Paul's First Missionary Journey, dated by conservative scholars like Hoehner to approximately AD 47-48. This is the very beginning of the organized Gentile mission.</li>\n<li><strong>Geospatial Data &amp; Physical Geography:</strong> Iconium (modern Konya, Turkey; 37.8715° N, 32.4846° E; altitude ~1027m) was a strategic city in the Roman province of Galatia, situated on the major east-west trade route. Its prominence made it a natural hub for missionary activity.</li>\n<li><strong>Original Audience Identification:</strong> The immediate audience of the book was a man named Theophilus (Acts 1:1), likely a high-ranking Roman official and a new believer. The wider audience was the burgeoning church, which needed a divinely inspired account of its own origins and the authentication of the apostolic gospel.</li>\n<li><strong>Author's Pastoral Situation (Text-Behind-the-Text):</strong> Luke writes as a meticulous historian (Luke 1:3) and a theologian. His purpose is to show Theophilus the certainty of the things he has been taught by demonstrating the unstoppable, Spirit-directed advance of the gospel from its Jewish center in Jerusalem to the heart of the Gentile world in Rome.</li>\n<li><strong>Socio-Political Background:</strong> Iconium was a Hellenized city with a significant Jewish population and a synagogue, which served as Paul's customary entry point for ministry. As part of the Roman Empire, it was under the rule of Roman law, which at this early stage was often indifferent or situationally hostile to the new Christian faith, depending on local politics and the influence of opponents.</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_e_verse_craft": "### Verse-Level Craft\n\nThis verse is a dense, participial-heavy summary of the ministry in Iconium, showcasing a divine-human partnership.\n\n*   **Linguistic Mechanics & Syntax:** The structure hinges on two present participles modifying \"the Lord\": τῷ μαρτυροῦντι (*tō martyrounti*, \"the one who bears witness\") and διδόντι (*didonti*, \"the one who grants\"). This grammatical choice portrays the Lord's actions as continuous and concurrent with the apostles' own ongoing action of \"speaking boldly\" (παρρησιαζόμενοι, *parrēsiazomenoi*). The apostles remain and speak; simultaneously, the Lord witnesses and grants. Their boldness is grounded ἐπὶ τῷ κυρίῳ (*epi tō kyriō*, \"in reliance on the Lord\"), indicating that their confidence was not in themselves, but was derived from their connection to and dependence on Him.\n*   **Imagery & Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):** The phrase \"through their hands\" (διὰ τῶν χειρῶν αὐτῶν, *dia tōn cheirōn autōn*) is a common biblical idiom for agency. The hands are not the source of power but the instruments through which God's power flows (cf. Acts 5:12; 19:11). This imagery reinforces that the apostles are conduits, not originators, of the miraculous, keeping the glory properly directed to God.\n*   **Literary Devices:** The phrase \"signs and wonders\" (σημεῖα καὶ τέρατα, *sēmeia kai terata*) is a stock phrase, almost a hendiadys, used throughout the Old Testament (LXX) and Acts to denote God's miraculous interventions in history. A σημεῖον (*sēmeion*, \"sign\") points to a theological reality, while a τέρας (*teras*, \"wonder\") evokes awe and astonishment. Together, they describe miracles that both authenticate the messenger and reveal the power of God.\n*   **Common Misreadings Flag:**\n    *   *Misreading:* Signs and wonders must accompany every effective gospel presentation today.\n    *   *Why wrong:* While God can and does still work miraculously, the Bible presents this specific, intense concentration of signs and wonders as a unique confirmation of new revelation, particularly in the eras of Moses, Elijah/Elisha, Christ, and the Apostles (Heb 2:3-4). It was a foundational, authenticating mark, not a normative requirement for all subsequent ministry.\n    *   *Cross-references:* Hebrews 2:3-4; 2 Corinthians 12:12.\n    *   *Correct reading:* God authenticated the apostolic message of grace with unique signs, and He remains sovereign to confirm His word today as He sees fit, primarily through the Spirit's work of regeneration.\n",
      "phase_e_verse_craft_html": "<h3>Verse-Level Craft</h3>\n<p>This verse is a dense, participial-heavy summary of the ministry in Iconium, showcasing a divine-human partnership.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Linguistic Mechanics &amp; Syntax:</strong> The structure hinges on two present participles modifying \"the Lord\": τῷ μαρτυροῦντι (<em>tō martyrounti</em>, \"the one who bears witness\") and διδόντι (<em>didonti</em>, \"the one who grants\"). This grammatical choice portrays the Lord's actions as continuous and concurrent with the apostles' own ongoing action of \"speaking boldly\" (παρρησιαζόμενοι, <em>parrēsiazomenoi</em>). The apostles remain and speak; simultaneously, the Lord witnesses and grants. Their boldness is grounded ἐπὶ τῷ κυρίῳ (<em>epi tō kyriō</em>, \"in reliance on the Lord\"), indicating that their confidence was not in themselves, but was derived from their connection to and dependence on Him.</li>\n<li><strong>Imagery &amp; Symbolism Rationale (Why This Image?):</strong> The phrase \"through their hands\" (διὰ τῶν χειρῶν αὐτῶν, <em>dia tōn cheirōn autōn</em>) is a common biblical idiom for agency. The hands are not the source of power but the instruments through which God's power flows (cf. Acts 5:12; 19:11). This imagery reinforces that the apostles are conduits, not originators, of the miraculous, keeping the glory properly directed to God.</li>\n<li><strong>Literary Devices:</strong> The phrase \"signs and wonders\" (σημεῖα καὶ τέρατα, <em>sēmeia kai terata</em>) is a stock phrase, almost a hendiadys, used throughout the Old Testament (LXX) and Acts to denote God's miraculous interventions in history. A σημεῖον (<em>sēmeion</em>, \"sign\") points to a theological reality, while a τέρας (<em>teras</em>, \"wonder\") evokes awe and astonishment. Together, they describe miracles that both authenticate the messenger and reveal the power of God.</li>\n<li><strong>Common Misreadings Flag:</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Misreading:</em> Signs and wonders must accompany every effective gospel presentation today.</li>\n<li><em>Why wrong:</em> While God can and does still work miraculously, the Bible presents this specific, intense concentration of signs and wonders as a unique confirmation of new revelation, particularly in the eras of Moses, Elijah/Elisha, Christ, and the Apostles (Heb 2:3-4). It was a foundational, authenticating mark, not a normative requirement for all subsequent ministry.</li>\n<li><em>Cross-references:</em> Hebrews 2:3-4; 2 Corinthians 12:12.</li>\n<li><em>Correct reading:</em> God authenticated the apostolic message of grace with unique signs, and He remains sovereign to confirm His word today as He sees fit, primarily through the Spirit's work of regeneration.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "phase_f_canonical": "### Canonical Connection\n\n*   **Foreshadowing & Fulfillment:** This event is a fulfillment of Jesus' promises to His apostles. He promised they would do \"greater works\" (John 14:12) and that signs would follow those who believe (Mark 16:17-20). Each miracle done \"through their hands\" is a validation of the authority of the resurrected Christ operating through His chosen witnesses. [PROPHECY]\n*   **Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):** The motif of \"God's word confirmed by signs\" runs through the entire Bible. It begins with God authenticating Moses before Pharaoh with signs and wonders (Exodus 4:1-9). It continues through prophets like Elijah, whose word is confirmed by fire from heaven (1 Kings 18:36-39). This trajectory finds its ultimate expression in Jesus, whose miracles were the primary testimony to His identity (John 5:36, \"the works that the Father has given me to accomplish...testify on my behalf\"). The apostles in Acts continue this pattern, demonstrating that the power of the resurrected Jesus is now at work through them. The *hinge-of-hinges* is the Resurrection itself, the ultimate sign. The *Christo-telic terminus* (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the ascended Christ empowering His Church by the Spirit (Acts 1:8).\n*   **Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:**\n    *   **Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):** The content of the message is \"the word of His grace,\" emphasizing that salvation is a free gift, not earned by works.\n    *   **Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"):** The boldness (παρρησία, *parrēsia*) of the apostles is a direct result of being filled with the Holy Spirit (cf. Acts 4:31).\n    *   **Bibliology (\"the doctrine of Scripture\"):** God Himself \"bears witness to the word.\" This affirms the divine origin and power of the proclaimed gospel message.\n    *   **Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):** This verse provides a paradigm for the Church's mission: a partnership where believers speak boldly in reliance on the Lord, who in turn confirms His word.\n*   **Theological Tension / Paradox:** The verse holds in perfect balance **divine sovereignty and human responsibility**. The apostles act with human agency: \"they remained,\" \"speaking boldly.\" Yet the efficacy and authentication are entirely divine: the Lord is the one \"bearing witness\" and \"granting\" the signs. They are 100% responsible to speak; He is 100% sovereign to confirm.\n*   **Aggregate Perspective & Tripartite Synthesis:** The Christian reading emphasizes this divine-human synergy as a model for mission. Jewish scholarship confirms the deep roots of \"signs and wonders\" (אותות ומופתים, *ʾōṯôṯ ûmôp̄əṯîm*) as the classic validation of a prophet sent from God, deliberately framing the apostles in the succession of Moses and Elijah. The Lord's confirmation of His Word is a core principle of divine communication in the Tanakh.\n*   **Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:** The \"Lord\" (τῷ κυρίῳ, *tō kyriō*) who bears witness is the Lord Jesus Christ, ascended and active. The \"word of His grace\" is the gospel *about* His finished work on the cross and His resurrection. The entire event is Christ-centric: His messengers speak His message in reliance on His power, and He confirms it with His authority.\n",
      "phase_f_canonical_html": "<h3>Canonical Connection</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Foreshadowing &amp; Fulfillment:</strong> This event is a fulfillment of Jesus' promises to His apostles. He promised they would do \"greater works\" (John 14:12) and that signs would follow those who believe (Mark 16:17-20). Each miracle done \"through their hands\" is a validation of the authority of the resurrected Christ operating through His chosen witnesses. [PROPHECY]</li>\n<li><strong>Motif Trajectory (Christo-telic):</strong> The motif of \"God's word confirmed by signs\" runs through the entire Bible. It begins with God authenticating Moses before Pharaoh with signs and wonders (Exodus 4:1-9). It continues through prophets like Elijah, whose word is confirmed by fire from heaven (1 Kings 18:36-39). This trajectory finds its ultimate expression in Jesus, whose miracles were the primary testimony to His identity (John 5:36, \"the works that the Father has given me to accomplish...testify on my behalf\"). The apostles in Acts continue this pattern, demonstrating that the power of the resurrected Jesus is now at work through them. The <em>hinge-of-hinges</em> is the Resurrection itself, the ultimate sign. The <em>Christo-telic terminus</em> (\"the Christ-event — incarnation, cross, resurrection, ascension, or Return — that this passage's trajectory ultimately points toward\") is the ascended Christ empowering His Church by the Spirit (Acts 1:8).</li>\n<li><strong>Systematic-Theology Loci Tag:</strong><ul>\n<li><strong>Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"):</strong> The content of the message is \"the word of His grace,\" emphasizing that salvation is a free gift, not earned by works.</li>\n<li><strong>Pneumatology (\"the doctrine of the Holy Spirit\"):</strong> The boldness (παρρησία, <em>parrēsia</em>) of the apostles is a direct result of being filled with the Holy Spirit (cf. Acts 4:31).</li>\n<li><strong>Bibliology (\"the doctrine of Scripture\"):</strong> God Himself \"bears witness to the word.\" This affirms the divine origin and power of the proclaimed gospel message.</li>\n<li><strong>Ecclesiology (\"the doctrine of the Church\"):</strong> This verse provides a paradigm for the Church's mission: a partnership where believers speak boldly in reliance on the Lord, who in turn confirms His word.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Theological Tension / Paradox:</strong> The verse holds in perfect balance <strong>divine sovereignty and human responsibility</strong>. The apostles act with human agency: \"they remained,\" \"speaking boldly.\" Yet the efficacy and authentication are entirely divine: the Lord is the one \"bearing witness\" and \"granting\" the signs. They are 100% responsible to speak; He is 100% sovereign to confirm.</li>\n<li><strong>Aggregate Perspective &amp; Tripartite Synthesis:</strong> The Christian reading emphasizes this divine-human synergy as a model for mission. Jewish scholarship confirms the deep roots of \"signs and wonders\" (אותות ומופתים, <em>ʾōṯôṯ ûmôp̄əṯîm</em>) as the classic validation of a prophet sent from God, deliberately framing the apostles in the succession of Moses and Elijah. The Lord's confirmation of His Word is a core principle of divine communication in the Tanakh.</li>\n<li><strong>Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:</strong> The \"Lord\" (τῷ κυρίῳ, <em>tō kyriō</em>) who bears witness is the Lord Jesus Christ, ascended and active. The \"word of His grace\" is the gospel <em>about</em> His finished work on the cross and His resurrection. The entire event is Christ-centric: His messengers speak His message in reliance on His power, and He confirms it with His authority.</li>\n</ul>",
