      "h1_title_html": "<p>Acts 14:5 — Unified Opposition and the Plot to Stone the Apostles</p>",
      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n> ὡς δὲ ἐγένετο ὁρμὴ τῶν ἐθνῶν τε καὶ Ἰουδαίων σὺν τοῖς ἄρχουσιν αὐτῶν ὑβρίσαι καὶ λιθοβολῆσαι αὐτούς,\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 15 rows = 105 cells.*\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | ὡς | hōs | G5613 | ὡς | Conj | as / when |\n| 2 | δὲ | de | G1161 | δέ | Conj | but / and (contrastive/connective) |\n| 3 | ἐγένεto | egeneto | G1096 | γίνομαι | V-ADI-3S | it happened / there arose |\n| 4 | ὁρμή | hormē | G3730 | ὁρμή | N-NSF | a rush / impulse / attempt |\n| 5 | τῶν | tōn | G3588 | ὁ | Art-GPN | of the |\n| 6 | ἐθνῶν | ethnōn | G1484 | ἔθνος | N-GPN | Gentiles / nations |\n| 7 | τε | te | G5037 | τέ | Conj | both (connects to καὶ) |\n| 8 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 9 | Ἰουδαίων | Ioudaiōn | G2453 | Ἰουδαῖος | A-GPM | of Jews |\n| 10 | σὺν | syn | G4862 | σύν | Prep | with (+dat) |\n| 11 | τοῖς | tois | G3588 | ὁ | Art-DPM | the |\n| 12 | ἄρχουσιν | archousin | G758 | ἄρχων | N-DPM | rulers / leaders |\n| 13 | αὐτῶν | autōn | G846 | αὐτός | P-GPM | of them / their |\n| 14 | ὑβρίσαι | hybrisai | G5195 | ὑβρίζω | V-AAN | to mistreat / insult outrageously |\n| 15 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 16 | λιθοβολῆσαι | lithobolēsai | G3036 | λιθοβολέω | V-AAN | to stone |\n| 17 | αὐτούς | autous | G846 | αὐτός | P-APM | them |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n> And when an impulse arose of both the Gentiles and Jews with their rulers to mistreat and to stone them,\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n> When an attempt was made by both the Gentiles and the Jews, with their rulers, to mistreat and stone them,\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n> But when a violent impulse [born of the city's division] arose, a hostile rush made by both the Gentiles and the Jews, together with their civic leaders, with the specific intent to inflict outrageous, shaming mistreatment upon them and then to stone them to death,\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>ὡς δὲ ἐγένετο ὁρμὴ τῶν ἐθνῶν τε καὶ Ἰουδαίων σὺν τοῖς ἄρχουσιν αὐτῶν ὑβρίσαι καὶ λιθοβολῆσαι αὐτούς,</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 15 rows = 105 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>ὡς</td>\n<td>hōs</td>\n<td>G5613</td>\n<td>ὡς</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>as / when</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>δὲ</td>\n<td>de</td>\n<td>G1161</td>\n<td>δέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>but / and (contrastive/connective)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>ἐγένεto</td>\n<td>egeneto</td>\n<td>G1096</td>\n<td>γίνομαι</td>\n<td>V-ADI-3S</td>\n<td>it happened / there arose</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>ὁρμή</td>\n<td>hormē</td>\n<td>G3730</td>\n<td>ὁρμή</td>\n<td>N-NSF</td>\n<td>a rush / impulse / attempt</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>τῶν</td>\n<td>tōn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-GPN</td>\n<td>of the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>ἐθνῶν</td>\n<td>ethnōn</td>\n<td>G1484</td>\n<td>ἔθνος</td>\n<td>N-GPN</td>\n<td>Gentiles / nations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>τε</td>\n<td>te</td>\n<td>G5037</td>\n<td>τέ</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>both (connects to καὶ)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαίων</td>\n<td>Ioudaiōn</td>\n<td>G2453</td>\n<td>Ἰουδαῖος</td>\n<td>A-GPM</td>\n<td>of Jews</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>σὺν</td>\n<td>syn</td>\n<td>G4862</td>\n<td>σύν</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>with (+dat)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>τοῖς</td>\n<td>tois</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-DPM</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>ἄρχουσιν</td>\n<td>archousin</td>\n<td>G758</td>\n<td>ἄρχων</td>\n<td>N-DPM</td>\n<td>rulers / leaders</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>αὐτῶν</td>\n<td>autōn</td>\n<td>G846</td>\n<td>αὐτός</td>\n<td>P-GPM</td>\n<td>of them / their</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>ὑβρίσαι</td>\n<td>hybrisai</td>\n<td>G5195</td>\n<td>ὑβρίζω</td>\n<td>V-AAN</td>\n<td>to mistreat / insult outrageously</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>λιθοβολῆσαι</td>\n<td>lithobolēsai</td>\n<td>G3036</td>\n<td>λιθοβολέω</td>\n<td>V-AAN</td>\n<td>to stone</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td>αὐτούς</td>\n<td>autous</td>\n<td>G846</td>\n<td>αὐτός</td>\n<td>P-APM</td>\n<td>them</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>And when an impulse arose of both the Gentiles and Jews with their rulers to mistreat and to stone them,</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>When an attempt was made by both the Gentiles and the Jews, with their rulers, to mistreat and stone them,</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But when a violent impulse [born of the city's division] arose, a hostile rush made by both the Gentiles and the Jews, together with their civic leaders, with the specific intent to inflict outrageous, shaming mistreatment upon them and then to stone them to death,</p>\n</blockquote>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** The faithful proclamation of the gospel will inevitably provoke hostile opposition from a world system that is spiritually unified against Christ.\n*   **FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):**\n    *   *Individual:* The fear of man—the temptation to soften the gospel's claims or remain silent to avoid rejection, mistreatment, or harm.\n    *   *Corporate:* The world's deep-seated, violent hatred of the exclusive claims of Jesus Christ, which can unite the most unlikely allies (religious and secular, different ethnicities, political rulers) in opposition to the Church.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Believers today may not face the threat of stoning in most parts of the world, but they face the same underlying hostility: public shaming (cancel culture), legal challenges, social ostracism, and workplace discrimination, often from coalitions of secular and pseudo-religious opponents.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Before we are called to face opposition, we must remember that Jesus Christ faced the ultimate plot. He endured the ultimate public shaming and the ultimate execution—the cross—in our place. He was not delivered from it but went through it to secure our salvation. Because He was victorious over that ultimate opposition through the resurrection, we can face lesser opposition with confidence in His sovereign protection and ultimate vindication.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* Do not be surprised by opposition (1 Pet 4:12). When you share the gospel, expect that some will respond with hostility.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a holy courage that is not naive. Be \"wise as serpents and innocent as doves\" (Matt 10:16), knowing when to stand your ground and when to flee to preserve your life for future ministry.\n    *   *Relational:* Pray for and support believers around the world who face the daily threat of violent persecution. Stand in solidarity with those in your own community who are being shamed or silenced for their faith.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* Be prepared to give a reason for the hope that is in you with gentleness and respect (1 Pet 3:15), knowing that even a gentle answer may be met with a hostile response.\n*   **Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):** The passage reveals God's sovereignty over the plans of men. We worship the God who grants His servants wisdom to escape danger and whose gospel advances not just in spite of opposition, but often because of it. \"You, O Lord, are a shield about me, my glory, and the lifter of my head\" (Ps 3:3).\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> The faithful proclamation of the gospel will inevitably provoke hostile opposition from a world system that is spiritually unified against Christ.</li>\n<li><strong>FCF (\"Fallen Condition Focus — the broken human condition the passage addresses\"):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Individual:</em> The fear of man—the temptation to soften the gospel's claims or remain silent to avoid rejection, mistreatment, or harm.</li>\n<li><em>Corporate:</em> The world's deep-seated, violent hatred of the exclusive claims of Jesus Christ, which can unite the most unlikely allies (religious and secular, different ethnicities, political rulers) in opposition to the Church.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars:</strong> Believers today may not face the threat of stoning in most parts of the world, but they face the same underlying hostility: public shaming (cancel culture), legal challenges, social ostracism, and workplace discrimination, often from coalitions of secular and pseudo-religious opponents.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Before we are called to face opposition, we must remember that Jesus Christ faced the ultimate plot. He endured the ultimate public shaming and the ultimate execution—the cross—in our place. He was not delivered from it but went through it to secure our salvation. Because He was victorious over that ultimate opposition through the resurrection, we can face lesser opposition with confidence in His sovereign protection and ultimate vindication.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> Do not be surprised by opposition (1 Pet 4:12). When you share the gospel, expect that some will respond with hostility.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a holy courage that is not naive. Be \"wise as serpents and innocent as doves\" (Matt 10:16), knowing when to stand your ground and when to flee to preserve your life for future ministry.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Pray for and support believers around the world who face the daily threat of violent persecution. Stand in solidarity with those in your own community who are being shamed or silenced for their faith.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> Be prepared to give a reason for the hope that is in you with gentleness and respect (1 Pet 3:15), knowing that even a gentle answer may be met with a hostile response.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Doxological Response (\"worship as the proper end of exegesis — adoration of God grounded in the passage's own disclosure\"):</strong> The passage reveals God's sovereignty over the plans of men. We worship the God who grants His servants wisdom to escape danger and whose gospel advances not just in spite of opposition, but often because of it. \"You, O Lord, are a shield about me, my glory, and the lifter of my head\" (Ps 3:3).</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:5 — \"...an attempt was made... to mistreat and to stone them.\"\nKEY TERM:     ὁρμή (*hormē*, \"a violent rush/impulse\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: The world's powers unite in a violent plot against the gospel's messengers.\nIMAGE:        Hands reaching for stones in the dusty street.\nAPPLICATION:  Pray for one persecuted believer or church by name this week.\nDOXOLOGY:     You, Lord, are the God who sees the plot and provides the way of escape.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:5 — &quot;...an attempt was made... to mistreat and to stone them.&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>ὁρμή (*hormē*, &quot;a violent rush/impulse&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>The world&#x27;s powers unite in a violent plot against the gospel&#x27;s messengers.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>Hands reaching for stones in the dusty street.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>Pray for one persecuted believer or church by name this week.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>You, Lord, are the God who sees the plot and provides the way of escape.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever hesitated to share your faith, fearing a negative reaction? The apostles Paul and Barnabas faced the ultimate negative reaction in the city of Iconium. After their preaching divided the city, Acts 14:5 tells us a plot was hatched. It wasn't just one group; it was a coalition of \"both the Gentiles and the Jews, with their rulers.\" Their plan was chillingly specific: first to publicly humiliate the apostles, then to execute them by stoning. This wasn't just bad luck; it was a fulfillment of Jesus' own warning that the world would hate His followers just as it hated Him (John 15:18).\n\nBut the story doesn't end with stones. The apostles became aware of the plot and fled, continuing their ministry in the next towns. Their story reminds us that opposition is not a sign of God's absence but often a confirmation of the gospel's power. Our Savior faced the ultimate plot and the cross itself, not to escape it, but to conquer sin and death for us. Because He is risen and reigns, we can have courage. We are called to be wise, but never to be silent. This week, perhaps you can pray for the courage of a believer somewhere in the world who faces a similar, violent threat for the sake of the name of Jesus.\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever hesitated to share your faith, fearing a negative reaction? The apostles Paul and Barnabas faced the ultimate negative reaction in the city of Iconium. After their preaching divided the city, Acts 14:5 tells us a plot was hatched. It wasn't just one group; it was a coalition of \"both the Gentiles and the Jews, with their rulers.\" Their plan was chillingly specific: first to publicly humiliate the apostles, then to execute them by stoning. This wasn't just bad luck; it was a fulfillment of Jesus' own warning that the world would hate His followers just as it hated Him (John 15:18).</p>\n<p>But the story doesn't end with stones. The apostles became aware of the plot and fled, continuing their ministry in the next towns. Their story reminds us that opposition is not a sign of God's absence but often a confirmation of the gospel's power. Our Savior faced the ultimate plot and the cross itself, not to escape it, but to conquer sin and death for us. Because He is risen and reigns, we can have courage. We are called to be wise, but never to be silent. This week, perhaps you can pray for the courage of a believer somewhere in the world who faces a similar, violent threat for the sake of the name of Jesus.</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What two specific violent acts were planned against Paul and Barnabas in Acts 14:5?\n    A: To mistreat (publicly humiliate) them and to stone them.\n2.  Who formed the coalition that plotted against the apostles?\n    A: A unified group of Gentiles, Jews, and their local civic rulers.\n3.  What does this event teach us about the nature of gospel ministry?\n    A: That faithful proclamation of Christ will provoke hostility from a world system unified against God. But our security is in Christ, who faced the ultimate opposition for us.\n4.  What is one practical way to respond to this passage's reality of persecution?\n    A: To pray specifically by name for a persecuted Christian or church, asking for their protection, wisdom, and courage.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What two specific violent acts were planned against Paul and Barnabas in Acts 14:5?\n    A: To mistreat (publicly humiliate) them and to stone them.</li>\n<li>Who formed the coalition that plotted against the apostles?\n    A: A unified group of Gentiles, Jews, and their local civic rulers.</li>\n<li>What does this event teach us about the nature of gospel ministry?\n    A: That faithful proclamation of Christ will provoke hostility from a world system unified against God. But our security is in Christ, who faced the ultimate opposition for us.</li>\n<li>What is one practical way to respond to this passage's reality of persecution?\n    A: To pray specifically by name for a persecuted Christian or church, asking for their protection, wisdom, and courage.</li>\n</ol>",
