      "h1_title_html": "<p>Acts 14:6 — Strategic Withdrawal as a Means of Gospel Advance</p>",
      "phase_a_text": "## The Text\n\n[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]\n\n**Original Script (NA28)**\n\n> συνιδόντες κατέφυγον εἰς τὰς πόλεις τῆς Λυκαονίας Λύστραν καὶ Δέρβην καὶ τὴν περίχωρον,\n\n**Interlinear Table**\n\n*Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.*\n\n| # | Greek | Translit. | Strong's | Lemma | Parsing | Literal Gloss |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | συνιδόντες | synidontes | G4894 | συνοράω | V-AAP-NPM | having become aware of / perceiving |\n| 2 | κατέφυγον | katephygon | G2723 | καταφεύγω | V-AAI-3P | they fled for refuge |\n| 3 | εἰς | eis | G1519 | εἰς | Prep | into / to |\n| 4 | τὰς | tas | G3588 | ὁ | Art-APF | the |\n| 5 | πόλεις | poleis | G4172 | πόλις | N-APF | cities |\n| 6 | τῆς | tēs | G3588 | ὁ | Art-GSF | of the |\n| 7 | Λυκαονίας | Lykaonias | G3071 | Λυκαονία | N-GSF | Lycaonia |\n| 8 | Λύστραν | Lystran | G3082 | Λύστρα | N-ASF | Lystra |\n| 9 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 10 | Δέρβην | Derbēn | G1191 | Δέρβη | N-ASF | Derbe |\n| 11 | καὶ | kai | G2532 | καί | Conj | and |\n| 12 | τὴν | tēn | G3588 | ὁ | Art-ASF | the |\n| 13 | περίχωρον | perichōron | G4066 | περίχωρος | A-ASF | surrounding region |\n\n**Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)**\n\n> having become aware, they fled for refuge to the cities of Lycaonia, Lystra and Derbe, and the surrounding region,\n\n**Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)**\n\n> but they learned of the plot and fled to the Lycaonian cities of Lystra and Derbe and to the surrounding region.\n\n**Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)**\n\n> But when Paul and Barnabas became fully aware [of the violent plot against them], they fled for refuge [as a deliberate, strategic act], making their way into the cities of the region of Lycaonia—specifically Lystra and Derbe—and into all the surrounding countryside [bringing the gospel to this new territory].\n",
      "phase_a_text_html": "<h2>The Text</h2>\n<p>[Pericope: Acts 14:1-7 · source: NA28]</p>\n<p><strong>Original Script (NA28)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>συνιδόντες κατέφυγον εἰς τὰς πόλεις τῆς Λυκαονίας Λύστραν καὶ Δέρβην καὶ τὴν περίχωρον,</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Interlinear Table</strong></p>\n<p><em>Interlinear: 7 columns × 11 rows = 77 cells.</em></p>\n<div class=\"vp-md-table-scroll\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>#</th>\n<th>Greek</th>\n<th>Translit.</th>\n<th>Strong's</th>\n<th>Lemma</th>\n<th>Parsing</th>\n<th>Literal Gloss</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>συνιδόντες</td>\n<td>synidontes</td>\n<td>G4894</td>\n<td>συνοράω</td>\n<td>V-AAP-NPM</td>\n<td>having become aware of / perceiving</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>κατέφυγον</td>\n<td>katephygon</td>\n<td>G2723</td>\n<td>καταφεύγω</td>\n<td>V-AAI-3P</td>\n<td>they fled for refuge</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>eis</td>\n<td>G1519</td>\n<td>εἰς</td>\n<td>Prep</td>\n<td>into / to</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>τὰς</td>\n<td>tas</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-APF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>πόλεις</td>\n<td>poleis</td>\n<td>G4172</td>\n<td>πόλις</td>\n<td>N-APF</td>\n<td>cities</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>τῆς</td>\n<td>tēs</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-GSF</td>\n<td>of the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Λυκαονίας</td>\n<td>Lykaonias</td>\n<td>G3071</td>\n<td>Λυκαονία</td>\n<td>N-GSF</td>\n<td>Lycaonia</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>Λύστραν</td>\n<td>Lystran</td>\n<td>G3082</td>\n<td>Λύστρα</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>Lystra</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>Δέρβην</td>\n<td>Derbēn</td>\n<td>G1191</td>\n<td>Δέρβη</td>\n<td>N-ASF</td>\n<td>Derbe</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>καὶ</td>\n<td>kai</td>\n<td>G2532</td>\n<td>καί</td>\n<td>Conj</td>\n<td>and</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>τὴν</td>\n<td>tēn</td>\n<td>G3588</td>\n<td>ὁ</td>\n<td>Art-ASF</td>\n<td>the</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>περίχωρον</td>\n<td>perichōron</td>\n<td>G4066</td>\n<td>περίχωρος</td>\n<td>A-ASF</td>\n<td>surrounding region</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p><strong>Faithful Direct Translation (formal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>having become aware, they fled for refuge to the cities of Lycaonia, Lystra and Derbe, and the surrounding region,</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Standalone English Translation (optimal equivalence)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>but they learned of the plot and fled to the Lycaonian cities of Lystra and Derbe and to the surrounding region.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Amplified Narrative Translation (meaning-based expansion)</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But when Paul and Barnabas became fully aware [of the violent plot against them], they fled for refuge [as a deliberate, strategic act], making their way into the cities of the region of Lycaonia—specifically Lystra and Derbe—and into all the surrounding countryside [bringing the gospel to this new territory].</p>\n</blockquote>",
      "phase_g_applications": "## Applications: So what?\n\n*   **Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):** God sovereignly uses opposition not to thwart His mission but to redirect it, turning persecution into a catalyst for gospel expansion into new territories.\n*   **Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):** The passage addresses two opposite errors. *Individual:* The fear of man that leads to silence and paralysis when faced with opposition. *Corporate:* The triumphalistic foolishness that mistakes recklessness for faith and refuses to retreat when prudence and stewardship of life demand it.\n*   **Shared Particulars:** Believers today, especially in contexts of persecution, face the same difficult decisions: when to speak boldly and endure, and when to relocate to preserve life for future ministry. The principle of strategic withdrawal for the sake of gospel advance remains relevant.\n*   **Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):** Because Christ has already won the ultimate victory over sin and death (Col 2:15), believers are freed from the need for self-preservation at all costs. Their lives are hidden with Christ in God (Col 3:3). This security empowers them to make wise, strategic decisions—whether to stay or to flee—based not on fear, but on what will best serve the advance of Christ's kingdom.\n*   **Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):**\n    *   *Personal — \"Doing\":* When facing opposition in a ministry context, prayerfully discern whether God is calling you to endure in place or to redeploy your efforts elsewhere. Do not automatically equate leaving with failing.\n    *   *Personal — \"Being\":* Cultivate a heart that is both courageous and wise, willing to speak boldly but also willing to retreat strategically for the sake of the mission.\n    *   *Relational:* Actively pray for and support missionaries and believers in persecuted regions, asking God to give them the wisdom of Paul and Barnabas to know when to stand and when to move.\n    *   *Public / Vocational:* In your workplace or community, when you encounter a \"closed door\" or opposition to a project or initiative, consider if it is a dead end or a divine redirection to a more fruitful area you hadn't considered.\n",
      "phase_g_applications_html": "<h2>Applications: So what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Universal Principle (\"the timeless theological truth derived from this passage\"):</strong> God sovereignly uses opposition not to thwart His mission but to redirect it, turning persecution into a catalyst for gospel expansion into new territories.</li>\n<li><strong>Fallen Condition Focus (FCF):</strong> The passage addresses two opposite errors. <em>Individual:</em> The fear of man that leads to silence and paralysis when faced with opposition. <em>Corporate:</em> The triumphalistic foolishness that mistakes recklessness for faith and refuses to retreat when prudence and stewardship of life demand it.</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Particulars:</strong> Believers today, especially in contexts of persecution, face the same difficult decisions: when to speak boldly and endure, and when to relocate to preserve life for future ministry. The principle of strategic withdrawal for the sake of gospel advance remains relevant.</li>\n<li><strong>Redemptive Indicative (Gospel Grounding):</strong> Because Christ has already won the ultimate victory over sin and death (Col 2:15), believers are freed from the need for self-preservation at all costs. Their lives are hidden with Christ in God (Col 3:3). This security empowers them to make wise, strategic decisions—whether to stay or to flee—based not on fear, but on what will best serve the advance of Christ's kingdom.</li>\n<li><strong>Imperative Applications (Spirit-empowered response to grace):</strong><ul>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Doing\":</em> When facing opposition in a ministry context, prayerfully discern whether God is calling you to endure in place or to redeploy your efforts elsewhere. Do not automatically equate leaving with failing.</li>\n<li><em>Personal — \"Being\":</em> Cultivate a heart that is both courageous and wise, willing to speak boldly but also willing to retreat strategically for the sake of the mission.</li>\n<li><em>Relational:</em> Actively pray for and support missionaries and believers in persecuted regions, asking God to give them the wisdom of Paul and Barnabas to know when to stand and when to move.</li>\n<li><em>Public / Vocational:</em> In your workplace or community, when you encounter a \"closed door\" or opposition to a project or initiative, consider if it is a dead end or a divine redirection to a more fruitful area you hadn't considered.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>",
      "memory_anchor": "## Memory Anchor Card\n```\nANCHOR VERSE: Acts 14:6 — \"...they learned of it and fled to Lystra and Derbe...\"\nKEY TERM:     κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, \"they fled for refuge\")\nSUBJECT → COMPLEMENT: A strategic retreat under pressure becomes a gospel advance to new fields.\nIMAGE:        Dusty footprints on a Roman road leading away from one city toward the frontier.\nAPPLICATION:  For the believer, view a closed door not as defeat, but as God's redirection.\nDOXOLOGY:     Lord, Your wisdom turns our persecution into Your proclamation.\n```\n",
      "memory_anchor_html": "<dl class=\"vp-anchor-card\"><dt>ANCHOR VERSE</dt><dd>Acts 14:6 — &quot;...they learned of it and fled to Lystra and Derbe...&quot;</dd><dt>KEY TERM</dt><dd>κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, &quot;they fled for refuge&quot;)</dd><dt>SUBJECT → COMPLEMENT</dt><dd>A strategic retreat under pressure becomes a gospel advance to new fields.</dd><dt>IMAGE</dt><dd>Dusty footprints on a Roman road leading away from one city toward the frontier.</dd><dt>APPLICATION</dt><dd>For the believer, view a closed door not as defeat, but as God&#x27;s redirection.</dd><dt>DOXOLOGY</dt><dd>Lord, Your wisdom turns our persecution into Your proclamation.</dd></dl>",
      "devotional_summary": "## Devotional Summary\nHave you ever faced a setback that felt like a total defeat? A door slammed shut, a plan crushed by opposition? In the book of Acts, we see how God uses the very thing that looks like failure to achieve His greatest victories. In the city of Iconium, the apostles Paul and Barnabas were preaching boldly, but their success stirred up dangerous opposition. A violent plot was formed to stone them to death. Their response wasn't a reckless last stand; it was a wise and strategic retreat.\n\nThe Bible says they \"learned of it and fled\" (Acts 14:6). But notice where they fled: to the unreached towns of Lystra and Derbe, in a rugged region called Lycaonia. This wasn't a panicked escape; it was a redeployment. The word used, κατέφυγον (*katephygon*, \"they fled for refuge\"), implies a deliberate move to a place of safety for the purpose of continuing the mission. The persecution that drove them out of one city was the very thing God used to push the good news into a brand new territory. Because Christ has secured our ultimate safety in Him, we are free to be wise. A closed door isn't always a sign of failure; sometimes, it's God's sovereign hand pointing us down a new road He wants us to travel for His glory. This week, when you face an obstacle, ask God: \"Are you closing this door to redirect me to a new field you have prepared?\"\n",
      "devotional_summary_html": "<h2>Devotional Summary</h2>\n<p>Have you ever faced a setback that felt like a total defeat? A door slammed shut, a plan crushed by opposition? In the book of Acts, we see how God uses the very thing that looks like failure to achieve His greatest victories. In the city of Iconium, the apostles Paul and Barnabas were preaching boldly, but their success stirred up dangerous opposition. A violent plot was formed to stone them to death. Their response wasn't a reckless last stand; it was a wise and strategic retreat.</p>\n<p>The Bible says they \"learned of it and fled\" (Acts 14:6). But notice where they fled: to the unreached towns of Lystra and Derbe, in a rugged region called Lycaonia. This wasn't a panicked escape; it was a redeployment. The word used, κατέφυγον (<em>katephygon</em>, \"they fled for refuge\"), implies a deliberate move to a place of safety for the purpose of continuing the mission. The persecution that drove them out of one city was the very thing God used to push the good news into a brand new territory. Because Christ has secured our ultimate safety in Him, we are free to be wise. A closed door isn't always a sign of failure; sometimes, it's God's sovereign hand pointing us down a new road He wants us to travel for His glory. This week, when you face an obstacle, ask God: \"Are you closing this door to redirect me to a new field you have prepared?\"</p>",
      "retention_quiz": "## Retention Quiz\n1.  What specific action did Paul and Barnabas take in response to the murder plot in Iconium?\n    A: They fled for refuge.\n2.  Why is the verb \"fled\" (κατέφυγον, *katephygon*) significant in this verse?\n    A: Its prefix suggests a deliberate, strategic flight to a place of refuge, not just a panicked escape.\n3.  What does this passage teach us about God's sovereignty over missionary work?\n    A: God uses opposition and persecution not to stop His mission but to redirect and expand it into new territories, proving His plans cannot be thwarted.\n4.  How can a believer apply the principle of this verse when facing a \"closed door\"?\n    A: The believer can prayerfully discern if the obstacle is a divine redirection to a different, more fruitful area of service, rather than simply a defeat.\n",
      "retention_quiz_html": "<h2>Retention Quiz</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What specific action did Paul and Barnabas take in response to the murder plot in Iconium?\n    A: They fled for refuge.</li>\n<li>Why is the verb \"fled\" (κατέφυγον, <em>katephygon</em>) significant in this verse?\n    A: Its prefix suggests a deliberate, strategic flight to a place of refuge, not just a panicked escape.</li>\n<li>What does this passage teach us about God's sovereignty over missionary work?\n    A: God uses opposition and persecution not to stop His mission but to redirect and expand it into new territories, proving His plans cannot be thwarted.</li>\n<li>How can a believer apply the principle of this verse when facing a \"closed door\"?\n    A: The believer can prayerfully discern if the obstacle is a divine redirection to a different, more fruitful area of service, rather than simply a defeat.</li>\n</ol>",
