n director of the mission (cf. Acts 13:2, 4; 16:6-7), guiding the apostles' steps through open and closed doors.</li>\n<li>☐ Soteriology (\"the doctrine of salvation in Christ\"): The flight is not the point; it is the means to the end of proclaiming the gospel of salvation (Acts 14:7), which is the entire purpose of the journey.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Theological Tension / Paradox:</strong> The passage holds in tension the virtues of boldness and prudence. In Iconium, the apostles \"spoke boldly for the Lord\" for a long time (14:3). Yet, faced with a credible murder plot, they fled. This resolves the false dichotomy between faith and common sense. True faith is not reckless; it is courageously obedient to God's leading, whether that means staying put or strategically relocating. This reflects Christ's own command to be \"wise as serpents and innocent as doves\" (Matt 10:16).</li>\n<li><strong>Christ-Centered Hermeneutic Verification:</strong> This passage points to Christ by demonstrating the outworking of His commission and commands. The apostles flee not to save their own lives for their own sake, but to preserve their lives for the sake of the gospel of Christ. Their actions are a testament to the supreme value they place on their message about Jesus, a message worth living—and relocating—to proclaim.</li>\n</ul>",
