e same concrete act. PASS — All center on discerning divine redirection in opposition.\n</code></pre>",
        "slide_deck_sidecar": "## Slide Deck Sidecar\n```markdown\n---\nbook: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"6\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre\n---\n\n# Acts 14:6 — Strategic Withdrawal as Gospel Advance\nThis single verse marks a pivotal moment in Paul's first missionary journey, where violent opposition in Iconium becomes the catalyst that pushes the gospel into the new region of Lycaonia, demonstrating God's sovereign power to turn setbacks into strategic advances for His kingdom.\n\n*Slide deck: 7 sections, 7 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.*\n",
        "slide_deck_sidecar_html": "<h2>Slide Deck Sidecar</h2>\n<h2>```markdown</h2>\n<p>book: \"Acts\"\nchapter: \"14\"\nsection: \"6\"\nvisual_palette: sepia parchment, dust-light, ochre</p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Acts 14:6 — Strategic Withdrawal as Gospel Advance</h1>\n<p>This single verse marks a pivotal moment in Paul's first missionary journey, where violent opposition in Iconium becomes the catalyst that pushes the gospel into the new region of Lycaonia, demonstrating God's sovereign power to turn setbacks into strategic advances for His kingdom.</p>\n<p><em>Slide deck: 7 sections, 7 total sub-slides, ≤5 bullets per slide.</em></p>",
        "cover_art_prompts": "## Cover Art Prompts\n\n```nano-banana-1\nAnchor: V1 lines 3-4 — \"They planned a deadly fire / For me and also you\"\nA cinematic still from behind two figures in simple, dusty traveler's robes, looking back over their shoulders at the gates of a Greco-Roman city (Iconium) at dusk. The city glows with torchlight, suggesting menace. The mood is tense and urgent. Sepia parchment tones, shot on 35mm film, anamorphic lens, with heavy grain and dust-light.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-2\nAnchor: Chorus lines 1-2 — \"The road from Iconium / Is where the mission starts\"\nAn ultra-wide cinematic shot of a worn Roman stone road stretching from the foreground into a vast, rugged, and empty Anatolian plateau under a dramatic sky. Two sets of footprints are visible in the dust on the road, leading away from the camera. The feeling is one of journey and divine purpose. Ochre and deep blue palette, golden hour light, volumetric light shafts breaking through clouds.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-3\nAnchor: V2 lines 1-2 — \"The stones were in their hands / Their angry plot was laid\"\nA shallow depth of field shot focusing on a pile of rough, heavy stones on the ground in a city alleyway. In the blurred background, angry shadows of a crowd are suggested but not clearly seen. The lighting is harsh chiaroscuro, creating a sense of imminent danger and violence. High-contrast sepia palette.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-4\nAnchor: Bridge lines 3-4 — \"So we could plant it down / The seed of His great grace\"\nA close-up, photorealistic shot of a hand letting a single, glowing seed fall from its palm onto dry, cracked earth. A single drop of water is about to land on the seed. The image is a tight macro, symbolizing the preciousness of the gospel being sown in new, hard ground. Warm amber light, shallow depth of field, shot on 35mm film.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-5\nAnchor: Outro lines 1-2 — \"To Lystra we will go / To Derbe we will run\"\nA cinematic still showing the two travelers arriving at the outskirts of a smaller, more rustic town (Lystra). They are looking toward it with determination, not fear. The landscape is rugged, the architecture simpler than the city they left. The mood is hopeful and resolute. Soft dawn gold palette, natural light.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-title\nAnchor: The Big Idea — \"Wise retreat is not cowardice but a divine strategy for redeploying gospel witnesses to new fields.\"\nA powerful cinematic image of two sets of footprints leading away from a pile of discarded stones on a dusty Roman road. The road stretches toward a distant, mountainous horizon under a vast, hopeful sky. The image captures the core theme: leaving danger behind to walk a new path of purpose. Sepia parchment and ochre palette, shot with an anamorphic lens for an epic feel.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n```nano-banana-horizon\nAnchor: Christo-telic Horizon — The Great Commission enacted.\nA symbolic, abstract image. A map of the ancient Roman world is etched onto a stone tablet. From a single point labeled \"Jerusalem,\" glowing lines of light spread outwards, with one bright line tracing the path from Iconium to Lystra and Derbe, pushing into a previously dark region of the map. The image visualizes the unstoppable advance of the gospel. Deep indigo and gold palette.\nNegative: no text, no watermarks, no logos, no modern dress, no anachronisms, no captions, no UI elements, no faces of named biblical figures except as symbolic representation.\n```\n",
